data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the EF Core Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous LINQ by internally wrapping async calls (sync-over-async) with an explicit opt-in. **In .NET 11, that sync-over-async bridge is removed entirely.** Calls like `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — the opt-in configuration is no longer honored.

This is because the underlying Azure Cosmos DB SDK is fundamentally async-only; the sync shim was always a stopgap.

## How to fix it

Convert all synchronous calls to their async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods → `async` + `Async` suffix
- Operators → `ToListAsync()`, `FirstAsync()`, `CountAsync()`, `SaveChangesAsync()`

This will cascade — all callers up the chain (controllers, services) must also go async. If you have many call sites, work top-down from the controller layer.
